[1] Canada (Yukon): early season onset
Date: 25 Nov 2016 7:13 PM CT
Source: CBC (Canadian Broadcasting Corporation) News [edited]
http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/flu-yukon-early-season-70-cases-1.3868967


Flu season has arrived with a vengeance in Yukon, with more than 70 confirmed cases as of 24 Nov 2016. Yukon normally averages 5 cases of confirmed influenza by 1 December each year, according to Dr Catherine Elliott, the territory's deputy chief medical officer of health. Of the confirmed cases, 86 per cent have been in Whitehorse. Cases in 3 rural communities have made up the remaining 14 per cent.

This surge of flu cases in Yukon is unusual, says Elliott. Most provinces and territories are reporting routine flu activity or no flu activity. Elliott says H3N2 is the strain of influenza being identified in the lab. It typically causes more severe illness.

As of 21 Nov 2016, 8 people have required hospitalization . Yukon normally sees an average of 7 flu hospitalizations over the entire 52-week flu season.

Dr Elliott is urging Yukoners to get flu shots, as this year's [2016-2017] vaccine protects against H3N2. If you think you have the flu, and you don't have any chronic conditions or risk factors for complications, Elliott advises staying home, and staying away from "people who might be vulnerable, like the elderly, the very young, people who are pregnant. But if you are in one of those vulnerable categories, then you should seek medical care as soon as possible." She also recommends washing your hands often and practising good coughing etiquette to keep viruses from spreading.

