[2] Reunion: impact in intensive care units
Date: Wed 24 Nov 2016
Source: Eurosurveillance 2016; 21(47) [edited]
http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=22649


[ref: Filleul L, Ranoaritiana DB, Balleydier E, et al. A major impact of the influenza seasonal epidemic on intensive care units, Reunion, April to August 2016. Euro Surveill. 2016; 21(47): pii=30405]
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Summary
-------
2016 seasonal influenza in Reunion in the southern hemisphere was dominated by influenza A(H1N1)pdm09 (possibly genogroup 6B.1). An estimated 100 500 patients with acute respiratory infection (ARI) consulted a physician (cumulative attack rate 11.9 per cent). 66 laboratory-confirmed cases (65.7/100 000 ARI consultations) were hospitalised in an intensive care unit, the highest number since 2009. Impact on intensive care units was major. Correlation between severe cases was 0.83 between Reunion and France and good for 2009 to 2015.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

The complete article is available at the source URL above.

"Reunion is a southern hemisphere French overseas territory with 843 529 inhabitants (2015 estimate) located in the Indian Ocean between Madagascar and Mauritius. The island benefits from a healthcare system similar to mainland France. In the 2016 influenza season, lasting from April to August, Reunion experienced a high number of severe influenza cases."

The study reports that an incidence rate of severe cases over the whole season was 65.7 per 100 000 ARI consultations in 2016, higher (1.5 times) than that observed in 2014 (46.0/100 000). The study also reports mainly influenza B virus circulation at the beginning of the epidemic period, and that influenza A(H1N1)pdm09 virus became the predominantly circulating virus later. Some A(H3N2) viruses were also detected, which accounted for only 20 percent of influenza viruses identified through surveillance. The study explored some common risk factors for influenza, such as chronic respiratory disease, diabetes, and cardiac disease, and did not observe any significant differences between previous seasons or type/subtype of viruses. There was low immunization coverage of around 34 percent in Reunion reported in the study.

The authors conclude that: "If a similar situation to that in Reunion happened during the 2016/17 influenza season in mainland France and potentially other European countries, we might observe an increase of severe influenza cases. This information can be useful to strengthen prevention, that is, by improving immunization coverage for the 2016/17 season and to prepare ICUs to be able to care for possibly more influenza patients than usual." - Mod.UBA

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Reunion Island can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4655906,531. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

